Neuromuscular impedance forces (FM) depended on three quantities: a muscular spring stiffness KSPR, a geometric stiffness KGEO, and a damping factor B. The quantity KSPR(θ, ψh) modeled the spring-like action of human musculotendon units, which was a function of the segmental geometry θ and a variable-stiffness rotational hip spring with stiffness ψh, which was previously estimated from real patient muscular moments M and joint kinematics during locomotion11,12. KGEO(θ, M) modeled how the limb endpoint stiffness due to muscular action is affected by skeletal geometry in the presence of a contact force13, which was a function of θ and M. Finally, damping B(KSPR) simulated the viscous effects of velocity-dependent muscular properties14, which was proportional to KSPR. These viscoelastic effects were expressed as4\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
